    "summary": "I became a UX designer because I have passion for art, a degree in (Computer) science, and a desire to make life easier and more enjoyable. It allows me to be analytical and organized when breaking down big and complex problems, ultimately creating well polished, engaging, and user-centric experiences out of them.\n\nIn 15+ years, I was lucky enough to work on a wide \u2013 and wild \u2013 range of projects; I worked on marketing campaign sites for Johnson & Johnson. Created concept art and coded scripts for social media games for Sony and Intel. Built design systems for Henry Schein\u2019s global marketplace. And pioneered the usage of design sprints in AB InBev to develop new features for their B2B app, creating rich interactive prototypes used in on-site user testing.\n\nI am devoted to crafting holistic product experiences, harnessing on the power of storytelling, marketing, and brand to make them delightful and evocative. I have data insights, experimentation, and user testing as powerful allies to inform my design decisions. I am committed to my peers in UX research, content, management, and engineering to ensure alignment throughout the design process. I use design thinking tools and methods to lead teams and navigate ambiguity, creating actionable next steps myself and others can follow.",
